segments.text: Well, Dr. Burns had a nice collection of dried poisonous plant specimens stored in Francis Hall over on campus.
That's where he taught plant toxicology.
And he had accumulated these.
So those were among the things that were to be moved.
He assigned, well, that was one of the, I can't remember.
I was trying to think of who it was.
It was involved with that.
Helms was involved.
who I think, he was probably the main one that was, got the idea that we'll just switch these, you know, we'll change the plants and the labels out.
Won't that be entertaining then for the next class that Dr. Burns, because Dr. Burns, the only reason that that would even occur maybe to someone would be because,

Dr. Burns was quite a storyteller and with most of those specimens he would, he could go on at some length just holding a specimen before the group and not only talking about what the effects would be but where it was exactly that he got that specimen and what the weather was like on that particular day.
I mean he could just
He could just amaze you, you know, going back in time and getting into great details.
And so the thought was that, well, he would pull out St. John's Ward or something like that, you know, and he would just look at the label and he would start talking about it.
And maybe if you had, if something entirely different, obviously different, was in the folder, if he didn't look at it, well, it would be...
amusing into one mindset.
So that was done, but then, of course, Dr. Burns, once he got out there, well, he went through each one of them.
Oh, he checked them.
He checked everything, yeah.
I know my involvement, I developed a new appreciation for the thoroughness and meticulous nature of a man because I was assigned to count
to inventory all of the rubber stoppers, which, when you say that, you think, well, an hour, maybe.
My gosh, he had rubber stoppers, and he had reserves, and he wanted everything counted, you know, in every size.
He wanted all of the different sizes.

I spent, I don't remember how long, but boy, and I tried, one of the reasons I spent that long was because shortly after I started, I kind of generalized and estimated, and I gave him a report when I was going off duty, and so when I came back a couple of days later, I had some time.
He had a little session with me, and he wanted me to understand that
My initial count was not satisfactory, and he did not intend an estimate.
He could estimate.
He wanted a count.
When you were in vet school, was there an honor system?
Yes.
As far as you know, did students follow it?
Well, I lost a classmate in my freshman year.

uh for cheating and this was done by the uh and there was guilt the honor council there was uh-huh were there others that you may have known about that were not caught not to my knowledge did you all sign an honor pledge yes uh-huh was there an explanation early early in the first year to explain what the honor system covered and everything
I've wondered why shouldn't the Corps have done that long ago?
Yeah, this was part of that first lecture, I think, with Al Price.
I believe that's when we got that.
I presume you're very proud of your A&M veterinary training.
Why are you proud of it?
What are the foundations of that pride?
Well, the faculty that taught me in vet school was, of course at the time I was a student, well I respected them as faculty, but
It was really in years after that that I think I developed my sense of appreciation for them and respect for them as it became fully developed.
You know, we had only 30-something faculty.
And so all of the department heads, for example,

all of the department heads in the vet school had substantial teaching loads and in general they taught the lead courses in their discipline and so to be able to go through with a group of very very respected
faculty of that stature, I've always felt very fortunate that I was able to do it.
You know, really and truly at the time that I finished, I had no way to know from a comparative standpoint how my education compared with what it might have been in some other state.
But as time has passed, well, I've developed
my appreciation for my education at Texas A&M has been increased.
Commencement, veterinary commencement was held, describe it as much as you recall, your year.
Where was it held?
Well, it was in G. Raleigh White, which was the new gym.
And we were seated on the floor, the main floor, I remember, and this was in... Was it just for vet school?
No, no, it was... Y'all were part of the larger one.
Uh-huh.
And this is the spring of 57.
Mm-hmm.
And it was, we were on, this was on Saturday morning.
I don't think, I think that was the only one.
And who came?
The only commencement.
Who came as your supporters?
Well, my parents were there and Ann's parents were there.
Oh, now you had met Ann by then.
Yeah, well, we married after my, at the end of my, well, on Saturday.
August 31st before my last year.
Oh, I forgot.
So she was down here for that.
So where did you all live that fourth year?
Well, we started out living in a duplex on Church Street there just where it's now gone for the, well, it was one block west, half a block west of A&M Presbyterian Church.
belonged to Zubik.
It was an apartment, a little duplex that belonged to Mr. Zubik.
But after, in October, I heard about one of the new large animal clinicians needing, looking for a married vet student
with no children who would move in with him and look after his little boy.
So this was Bill Romaine and little Bill.
And so we did that.
Lived over on Jersey Street and across the street from the

basketball coach that had been brought in from the northeast that was to oh yeah yeah yeah um the one before shelby before shelby between rogers and shelby i can't think of it right now but anyway we lived over there across the street from him on jersey street and uh
And so when, how did you, what were your future dreams when you graduated?
What did you think you were going to do?
Well, I had already agreed to accept to take the instructorship in anatomy.
And my plan was to, at that point, was to evaluate
education as a career possibility and but I still felt I felt it at the time that I stayed and made the decision that I still felt compelled to go into practice and evaluate that further.
Now this this job this instructorship what was the pay of that?
Well it was

it was fifty one hundred dollars for twelve months and uh... uh... dr armistead got into trouble with that as i learned later because pat hubert who had graduated two or three years before was making only five thousand in large animal clinic and uh...
So as you walked across the stage, it was then every name called, every hand shaken, and you felt optimistic about your future.
Yeah.
If you were now giving advice to the College of Veterinary Medicine leadership,
You're now their consultant.
You're giving them advice about undergraduate or non-graduate post-DVM training.
What advice would you give them about veterinary instruction, the DVM instruction?
What to hold on to and what to...
I'd have to think about that, I believe, because, see, it is so different now to anything.
And I know it's different, but I don't know the particulars of that difference.
See, there are, the students have, they interact with,
with many more faculty members.
And only a portion of those faculty are knowledgeable, really knowledgeable, of the profession that the students are preparing for.
Because they're not veterinarians.
They are research people.
In many instances, most instances, they're quite successful in their research endeavors.
And they are doing this as part of the obligations of their position.
And that's where we've evolved to, I guess.
So I don't know.
Best I can.
that I've been able to determine in the last 10 years of observing that this seems to, you know, I don't see any major deficiencies coming from it, but I really don't know.
Alright, then the last thing I have to ask is what feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M today?
Well,
It's just A&M is a part of me.
I'm not a rah-rah type supporter, if you will.
But what happens is very important in the way of things being done well.
You know, I'm so pleased that we have had the president we've had in the last few years.
I can see it takes no imagination at all to see how that tragedy could have been visited upon tragedy with this bonfire thing if we had not had the right person there.
And I think he was about as right as I can think of anyone.
any other person or any other traits that I would have liked to have seen in command at that time.
I'm very pleased and have just really been amazed through the years at how the student body has continued at Texas A&M, the student body has continued to be
hold the values, hold the same things important that we did when I was in that small group of chauvinistic male students, non-segregated.
I mean totally segregated.
What creates that spirit?
Why?
It's a puzzle to me.
I have spent a lot of time thinking about that.
Now certainly there are a lot of other influences that the new students go through.
I've never been to a fish camp, for example.
I'm curious what the environment is there.
I can't help but wonder if fish camp isn't a several day enactment of what we used to get in the halls of what I got in the hallways of dorm 14
after CQ each night for the first month.
That was routine.
We were in CQ studying until 10.30 or 11 o'clock on Sunday and Wednesday night.
And then we would have anywhere from a half hour to two or three hours in the halls with one of the upperclassmen at a time
holding forth a discourse on this or that or the other about A&M and what you shall do and what you shall not do and so on.
Can A&M Spirit really be described to somebody that hasn't experienced it?
I can't imagine it.
It can be described, but I can't imagine there being an appreciation for what has been described.
You know, we were in... Ann and I were... Ann accompanied me to a meeting in Chicago, and we were there when the bonfire collapsed.
And...
The news accounts and the interviews seem to communicate to some of the people on the street types there in Chicago.
I know when we were on our way out and we got to, we took a cab out to O'Hare and when we unloaded our luggage, well,
there was an A&M sticker on stuck on one of them and there was a black man one of the people working there who saw that and asked us about the bonfire and it was almost he was

emotional about it about the tragedy of it and he expressed a curiosity about that school and asked two or three questions about is it really true that the students do this or and I was struck by by how you know all of the interviewing and all of the time that had been devoted to that that it
that some of the people were getting a little bit of an insight.
Of course, many others only saw it as akin to a college prank gone awry type thing.
What I'm looking for is the form that you and I need to sign.
And I believe that I have, for the first time,
fail to bring one.
So I'll have to get that out to you.
So let's close with what are your hopes for A&M future, particularly in veterinary medicine?
Well, I'd like

hope that they're able to maintain the course that they're on right now I guess I don't see a need for well they're little things but I won't I don't see that those need to be they're not that important but when you when I look at the
the course that the vet school is on, we have a real strong, the students are adequately educated before they get to the clinics.
They have a tremendous clinical education program.
And there is truly a

a broad based research program it's both basic and clinical so you're on a real good course right now I we could talk about them taking leadership in in going to new forms of education where of veterinary education where
parts of it are done away from the main campus.
That's for a later generation than me.
I'm too much of a traditionalist to be advocating that.
I'd like to see them really continuing on in the direction that they are.
There is a, you know, I do have a concern, I guess, for veterinary medicine in general and that is I don't know where the faculties of the future will come from other than
the people whose primary strength is research.
I do not feel that veterinary education can be successful without there being a core of veterinarians involved as teachers.
And there are, it's becoming less and less attractive, well veterinary academia is becoming less and less competitive all the time and this is not from the standpoint of money.
is salary differentials.
That's not the big issue.
The big issue is the problem with, well, longevity.
You know, I still feel in my discussions even in recent years that veterinary medicine, I think,

could prosper if we could just get tenure completely out of the picture and just have i think that there would be a lot of people in veterinary medicine who would be interested in going into academia without any lifetime assurances of employment or anything that's the way i that was never a consideration for me in
whether I would go into academia or not, was that, well, if I do that and if I can get by the first few years, I'll be set for life.
That's not part of it at all.
But, you know, the thing that's so crippling with the tenure system is you're either in or you're out in a few years.
And with the opportunities in industry and a number of other
in private diagnostic laboratories and research labs and things like that.
There's no problem with that.
Neither are they guaranteed a lifetime employment.
But also, they are not treated as second-class citizens after year six or seven or whatever.
But you're, in summary, you're optimistic about the program today and where it's headed.
Well, I am, uh-huh, as far as the iteration that we have here for veterinary medicine.
But I am, the one concern I have is,
to address the need to eliminate this big problem in recruiting and attracting bright young people into a veterinary career.
We've had two or three of the people that I was involved with most recently in their training who have just been
Well, they weren't really just bought by industry, but they were offered very lucrative situations.
But the final nail was driven by the uncertainty of what tenure would do.
Yet when they went to their jobs, they did not go to a lifetime position.
And so somehow we need
to be able to address that.
I'm sure that's not just in veterinary medicine.
I was enticed into academia, as I see it, at the beginning of a

an expansion of veterinary medical education in North America you know we had a number of veterinary schools that were established in the sixties and seventies they required more faculty and we had of course before that well a number of the existing veterinary schools increased their enrollment which required more faculty and Armistead was one of the visionaries that saw that well these
34 faculty members aren't going to be equal to the task of classes of 100.
And where are we going to get the people?
So he had already started these instructorships, and that was the best he had at that time.
Because the pool of faculty had gotten very, very small.

And I'm concerned that we're going to be looking at that in the future here in this country and at A&M even, that one of these days you're going to wake up to the fact we're going to need some more faculty.
And where are we going to get them?
This is not something you do in a year or two.
Armistead was starting it, and other places were starting it in the mid-50s.
And yet it really wasn't critical
Didn't become critical until the mid 60s.

So about a 10 year you need about a 10 years Jump on it and I don't see that happening anywhere really We were really losing There has been a decrease in the number of funded graduate positions graduate training positions I think is compared to in the 80s whenever I think that's when it peaked in veterinary medicine and
So that's gonna need, we're gonna need that turnaround sometime in the future.
Let's quit with that.
I found the sheet.
